{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Parallelogram Rule"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "One of the most striking properties of learned word embeddings is that semantic relationships appear as consistent vector offsets. The \"king−man+woman≈queen\" example is not a one-off curiosity: the offset vector that points from \"man\" to \"woman\" is nearly identical to the offset from \"king\" to \"queen\", from \"actor\" to \"actress\", from \"uncle\" to \"aunt\". The geometry of the embedding space encodes the relationship as a direction."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Left: 2D vector space showing man, woman, king, queen as a parallelogram — horizontal axis captures royalty/power, vertical axis captures gender. The analogy king−man+woman points directly to queen. Right: table of semantic and syntactic analogy categories from the Google Analogy Dataset with accuracy bars for GloVe and Word2Vec."}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Solving Analogies with 3CosAdd"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The standard solver is called 3CosAdd. Given the analogy \"a is to b as c is to ?\", it finds the vocabulary word "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "d"}, {"type": "text", "text": " that maximises:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "d^* = \\arg\\max_{d \\in V \\setminus \\{a,b,c\\}} \\cos(\\mathbf{v}_d,\\; \\mathbf{v}_b - \\mathbf{v}_a + \\mathbf{v}_c)"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The candidate words "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "a"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "b"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", and "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "c"}, {"type": "text", "text": " are excluded from the search to prevent trivial solutions."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import gensim.downloader as api\nimport numpy as np\n\nwv = api.load(\"glove-wiki-gigaword-300\")\n\ndef solve_analogy(a, b, c, wv, topn=5):\n    \"\"\"\n    a is to b as c is to ?\n    Returns the topn candidate words using 3CosAdd.\n    \"\"\"\n    return wv.most_similar(\n        positive=[b, c],\n        negative=[a],\n        topn=topn,\n    )\n\n# king - man + woman\nprint(solve_analogy(\"man\", \"king\", \"woman\", wv, topn=3))\n# [('queen', 0.85), ('princess', 0.76), ('monarch', 0.74)]\n\n# Paris - France + Italy\nprint(solve_analogy(\"france\", \"paris\", \"italy\", wv, topn=3))\n# [('rome', 0.89), ('milan', 0.78), ('naples', 0.71)]\n\n# walk - walked + ran\nprint(solve_analogy(\"walked\", \"walk\", \"ran\", wv, topn=3))\n# [('run', 0.88), ('sprint', 0.74), ('jog', 0.71)]"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Evaluation: The Google Analogy Dataset"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Mikolov et al. released a benchmark of 19 558 analogy pairs split into two categories:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Semantic (8 869 pairs, 9 categories)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": capitals of countries, currencies, family relationships, opposites, etc."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Syntactic (10 675 pairs, 5 categories)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": adjective→adverb, plural, past tense, comparative, superlative."}]}]}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# Gensim has a built-in evaluator for this dataset\nresult = wv.evaluate_word_analogies(\n    \"questions-words.txt\"   # the Google analogy file\n)\n\noverall_accuracy = result[0]   # fraction of analogies solved correctly\nprint(f\"Overall accuracy: {overall_accuracy:.1%}\")\n\nfor section in result[1]:\n    name  = section[\"section\"]\n    corr  = len(section[\"correct\"])\n    total = corr + len(section[\"incorrect\"])\n    print(f\"  {name}: {corr}/{total} ({corr/total:.0%})\")"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why Does This Work?"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The linear structure emerges from the training objective. When the model learns to predict \"river\" from \"bank\" and \"financial\" from \"bank\", the two senses pull the \"bank\" vector in different directions. Words with the same relationship — man/king, woman/queen — appear in nearly identical distributional contexts shifted by the \"royalty\" dimension, so the model learns the same offset for both pairs."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "This is not a guaranteed outcome of any embedding method — it emerges specifically because the training corpus contains regularities in how humans write about gendered roles, countries and their capitals, and so on. The geometry of the embedding space is a mirror of the geometry of language use."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Limits and Failure Cases"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Rare words fail"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": if \"Bishkek\" (capital of Kyrgyzstan) appears only 100 times in the corpus, its vector is noisy and the capital–country analogy breaks."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Polysemy confounds offsets"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": \"bank\" has a mixed vector; analogies involving polysemous words often fail."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Benchmark inflation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": a model that memorised the test words during training scores high without having learned the relationship. Test words should be held out from hyper-parameter tuning."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "3CosAdd vs. 3CosMul"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": an alternative formula multiplies cosine similarities instead of adding vectors and often outperforms 3CosAdd on the same model."}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "3CosMul formula"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "d^* = \\arg\\max_{d} \\frac{\\cos(\\mathbf{v}_d, \\mathbf{v}_b)\\, \\cos(\\mathbf{v}_d, \\mathbf{v}_c)}{\\cos(\\mathbf{v}_d, \\mathbf{v}_a) + \\varepsilon}"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Practical Uses of Analogy Structure"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Bias auditing"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": the analogy \"man:doctor :: woman:nurse\" reveals occupational gender bias in the training corpus (Bolukbasi et al., 2016)."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Cross-lingual transfer"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": if English and French embedding spaces are aligned, the offset from \"cat\" to \"chat\" generalises — you can translate unseen words by applying the offset."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Domain adaptation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": analogy probing on a domain corpus tells you whether entity relationships (drug:side-effect, gene:protein) were captured during training."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Embedding sanity checks"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": after training embeddings on a new corpus, solving a handful of known analogies is a fast check that training converged correctly."}]}]}]}]}}